were nasty. They don't

00:15:15.750 --> 00:15:20.350
welcome innovation.
Science is very hostile to

00:15:20.350 --> 00:15:25.070
innovation when it challenges
existing theory,

00:15:25.070 --> 00:15:29.780
sort of like management,
the same thing. Let's move onto

00:15:29.780 --> 00:15:34.490
something that really took the giant
step ahead, and that was Mendeleev.

00:15:34.490 --> 00:15:39.210
And I also want to mention Lothar
Meyer in Tubingen who came up with

00:15:39.210 --> 00:15:43.920
the same classification scheme,
but we are going to see in a moment

00:15:43.920 --> 00:15:48.640
why Meyer is not well celebrated
today and the glory to

00:15:48.640 --> 00:15:52.900
goes to Mendeleev.
1869, Mendeleev,

00:15:52.900 --> 00:15:56.720
here is a picture of him taken from
that period. He was 35 years old at

00:15:56.720 --> 00:16:00.540
the time he enunciated this.
35, positively brilliant. Here is

00:16:00.540 --> 00:16:04.360
his paper. It was published in The
Journal of Russian Chemical Society,

00:16:04.360 --> 00:16:08.180
1869. And it is really great
because he actually goes through the

00:16:08.180 --> 00:16:26.960
thought process for you
and describes --

00:15:52.000 --> 00:16:16.370
I need to give you one piece of
background. Mendeleev played cards.

00:16:16.370 --> 00:16:20.740
And he traveled by train. And so
to pass the time,

00:16:20.740 --> 00:16:25.120
he would play solitaire.
He was used to working with cards

00:16:25.120 --> 00:16:29.490
and putting things in rows and
columns by suit.

00:16:29.490 --> 00:16:33.870
You had to find what is the
distinguishing feature?

00:16:33.870 --> 00:16:38.240
Well, these are all clubs,
these are all spades and these are

00:16:38.240 --> 00:16:42.620
all hearts. And I get down to a
certain card and I am stumped,

00:16:42.620 --> 00:17:02.373
so I will leave a space waiting for
that card to appear on cue.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:50.640
That is the background.
Here he is. He has all the

00:16:50.640 --> 00:16:54.290
information he knows that has been
reported on the various elements on

00:16:54.290 --> 00:16:57.930
file cards. He even carried them
around in his pocket and he would

00:16:57.930 --> 00:17:01.580
look at them from time to time and
try to devise a scheme.

00:17:01.580 --> 00:17:05.230
Remember the other people,
the octaves had been enunciated,

00:17:05.230 --> 00:17:08.870
the triads had been enunciated.
Here he is in his paper and says at

00:17:08.870 --> 00:17:12.520
that time I decided that it was
advantageous to find a more general

00:17:12.520 --> 00:17:16.170
system of the elements and here is
my attempt. And here he

00:17:16.170 --> 00:17:20.660
has laid them all out.
And he has left blanks here,

00:17:20.660 --> 00:17:25.990
question marks here and says it is
advantageous to put them in rows and

00:17:25.990 --> 00:17:31.330
to form a table.
And here is the smoking gun

00:17:31.330 --> 00:17:36.660
sentence right here.
It says finally it came to place,

00:17:36.660 --> 00:17:41.990
according to this concocted system,
and I've underlined in red, very

00:17:41.990 --> 00:17:47.330
many undiscovered members.
So what does he do? He knows that

00:17:47.330 --> 00:17:52.460
he shouldn't put arsenic under --
He shouldn't put arsenic under

00:17:52.460 --> 00:17:57.380
aluminum. Arsenic is nothing like
aluminum. Arsenic is like

00:17:57.380 --> 00:18:02.300
phosphorus. He takes those two
facts, plus the courage to leave

00:18:02.300 --> 00:18:07.220
blanks, and this is what he gives us.
Lothar Meyer was doing the same

00:18:07.220 --> 00:18:12.150
thing, but Mendeleev does something
more. He says not only does arsenic

00:18:12.150 --> 00:18:17.070
belong under phosphorus,
I predict that there is an element

00:18:17.070 --> 00:18:34.873
that lies below aluminum
and above indium.

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:26.300
And I will go even further and will
predict what its atomic mass is.

00:18:26.300 --> 00:18:30.610
So he called them eka. Eka comes
from Sanskrit meaning one after.

00:18:30.610 --> 00:18:34.920
So eka-aluminum is one after
aluminum. He predicted 68 for the

00:18:34.920 --> 00:18:39.230
atomic mass. Gallium was
subsequently isolated 69.

00:18:39.230 --> 00:18:43.530
. Eka-silicon, which we now know to
be germanium, 72,

00:18:43.530 --> 00:18:47.840
72.6. He says there is an element
under zirconium, and it

00:18:47.840 --> 00:18:51.770
should be about 180.
He said there should be an element

00:18:51.770 --> 00:18:55.330
under boron. He called it eka-boron,
scandium 45, 45.

00:18:55.330 --> 00:18:58.880
. It gets better.
He goes into excruciating detail.

00:18:58.880 --> 00:19:02.440
This is his prediction for silicon.
I already showed you the atomic

00:19:02.440 --> 00:19:05.990
mass. He said I predict its density
5.5. It was measured 5.

00:19:05.990 --> 00:19:09.550
6. He says it will have a high
melting point.

00:19:09.550 --> 00:19:13.110
Well, that is arbitrary.
It melts at 958. It forms a

00:19:13.110 --> 00:19:16.660
dioxide, has a high melting point.
And he predicts the density of the

00:19:16.660 --> 00:19:20.220
oxide of the yet undiscovered
element. And he gets it right to

00:19:20.220 --> 00:19:23.920
two significant figures.
And then he says the tetrachloride

00:19:23.920 --> 00:19:27.780
will be volatile,
and it will have a density of 1.

00:19:27.780 --> 00:19:31.640
. And subsequently germanium
tetrachloride was synthesized and

00:19:31.640 --> 00:19:35.490
measured to be 1.
8. That is why we celebrate

00:19:35.490 --> 00:19:39.350
Mendeleev. What we are seeing here
is a big transition from just

00:19:39.350 --> 00:19:43.210
experiment and documentation to
modern chemistry.

00:19:43.210 --> 00:19:47.070
And how does modern chemistry work?
Well, first of all, look at the

00:19:47.070 --> 00:19:50.880
data.
We always have to look around us and

00:19:50.880 --> 00:19:54.640
account for all the evidence.
And this is an ethical question,

00:19:54.640 --> 00:19:58.410
people. Sometimes you get data that
throw you off.

00:19:58.410 --> 00:20:02.170
And it is so easy to dismiss those
data. What you have to do is have

00:20:02.170 --> 00:20:05.930
the courage to say I have got to
account for the bad data,

00:20:05.930 --> 00:20:09.700
what I think are bad data and the
data that helped me build my theory.

00:20:09.700 --> 00:20:13.460
So you recognize patterns and then
develop a model,

00:20:13.460 --> 00:20:17.230
and most desirably a quantitative
model. A quantitative model that

00:20:17.230 --> 00:20:35.860
explains the observations,
obviously.

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:25.140
But what Mendeleev did was he came
up with a model that not only

00:20:25.140 --> 00:20:29.280
explained what we observed.
It made prediction. And it made

00:20:29.280 --> 00:20:33.420
predictions that can be tested.
I would love to make predictions

00:20:33.420 --> 00:20:37.560
that you cannot test.
Well, let's make predictions that

00:20:37.560 --> 00:20:41.710
can be put to the test.
So this is modern chemistry.

00:20:41.710 --> 00:20:45.850
I have told you about the table of
the elements. Why do we call it the

00:20:45.850 --> 00:21:05.033
Periodic Table?
